[00:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Guys, today is an exciting day because we\'re going to be looking at the brand new Insta360 Luna Ultra. Let\'s go ahead and switch to this camera right now. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[00:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; All right, and now we\'re recording on the Luna Ultra. And right off the bat, let me tell you about some of the exciting features we\'re going to be talking about in today\'s video. [music] The Luna Ultra is Insta360\'s first ever with a full 1-in sensor. On top of that, it\'s also the first Insta360 camera to'

[00:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get 10-bit color, making i-log better than ever. It features two cameras, a 20-mm 1x camera and a 60-mm 3x camera with the ability to zoom up to 12x. That is a 240-mm'

[00:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'equivalent. And it can shoot in 8K 30 frames per second, which as you can see on screen right now, that 8K is no joke. We\'re not talking about upscaled, we\'re talking about real detail and'

[00:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'resolution. On top of all of that, we\'re also going to look at the autofocus and bokeh, low-light performance, subject tracking capabilities, photo capabilities, audio tests, and the feature that I think is the most game-changing, the detachable screen.'

[01:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, we\'re going to get to all of that. [music] Now, as a disclaimer, this showcase video is sponsored by Insta360, but I\'m telling you there is so much to see here. And if you\'re interested in seeing some independent reviews as well'

[01:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as comparisons, get subscribed because there\'s going to be so much more content covering this camera space. I\'m telling you guys, this generation of pocket cameras is going to absolutely change content creation and mobile filmmaking.'

[01:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All right. Let\'s roll. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; To kick things off, we\'ve got to take a'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at the image quality coming out of this camera. First, I just want to show you how good the 8K I-Log 10-bit footage is. Now that Insta360 has finally upgraded from 8-bit color, we\'re getting such good color detail out of our'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'footage. As you can see, Insta360\'s conversion LUT to go from I-Log to Rec. 709 looks amazing with no additional processing. So, for those of us who love getting that cinematic non-digital look from I-Log, you can actually still turn'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around a video quite quickly with just a drag and drop of their conversion LUT. Then, of course, thanks to that 10-bit color, we\'re able to push that image even further when it comes to color grading to really dial in a specific creative look that suits the mood of our projects. The 8K footage combined with'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the I-Log and turning down the in-camera sharpness, we\'re able to achieve a level of resolution and color depth that we\'ve rarely seen from cameras of this form factor. Not to say that it hasn\'t been done before, but it\'s definitely a strong contender for the best footage'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ve seen from a camera like this. And I can definitely say that this is the best footage I\'ve gotten out of an Insta360 camera to date. Combined with the fact that we\'ve got two different focal lengths of 20 mm and 60 mm, along with the solid digital zoom performance, you'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can now get a variety of perspectives all from a camera that fits in your pocket. One of the biggest things that held back cameras of this form factor in the past was definitely the fact that you were really stuck with just a wide-angle field of view. But now that'

[03:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re able to mix in all of those different perspectives and compositions, it really elevates what this camera can do. Plus, we even have 4K 120 frames slow motion to add to the repertoire. While these are limited to just 20 mm'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and 60 mm, so you aren\'t able to zoom into 6 or 12x, I\'m focused on the fact that you can get beautiful-looking slow motion at two different focal lengths. And if you\'re somebody who\'s really not that interested in using LUTs and'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'editing on your computer and you just want to see what the footage looks like out of the camera, well, we have good news here, too, because the normal color profile looks incredibly good. Colors are true to life, vibrant, and full of contrast, and look great straight out of'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the camera. This is especially great for those who just want a good camera to take with them on trips or with their family. Believe it or not, the majority of this footage I shot for this video was filmed in auto white balance and auto exposure set to minus 0.3 or minus'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '0.7, and both the white balance and exposure looked great in just about every shot, making this one of the easiest cameras I\'ve used to date. And if you want that high dynamic range look, there\'s actually a mode in the'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Lumix Ultra called Dolby Vision, which is their new HDR format that they have in this camera, and basically what that does is it protects the highlights, protects the shadows, gives you a little bit more of that range in your footage,'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and again, it\'s super easy right out of the camera, which you\'re looking at on screen right now. Overall, the footage coming out of the Lumix Ultra is going to surprise a lot of people. All right, so let\'s talk about the two cameras that'

[04:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make this possible. Starting off with the first one, the wide angle in the main camera, and that\'s going to be the 20 mm 1X lens that has a 1-in sensor and an F1.8 aperture lens. And with a 1-in sensor and an F1.8 aperture, that means'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'low light on this camera is going to be really good, and we\'re going to test that later in the low light section, but it also means that we\'re getting some of that real bokeh, that real depth. And then we\'ve got the second camera, which'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is sporting a smaller 1/1.3-in sensor, but it\'s got a 60 mm lens with an F2 aperture. So again, look at all of that real bokeh, that looks so good. And on top of all that, Insta360 claims 14'

[05:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stops of dynamic range, which should be more than enough for most shooting scenarios. Now, let\'s talk about zoom real quick. Everything from 1X all the way up to 2.9x is going to be utilizing the 20 mm camera. And then everything'

[05:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from 3x all the way up to 12x is going to be utilizing the 60 mm camera. And if you\'re shooting in 4K, you can actually zoom all the way from 1x all the way up to 12x and back without stopping recording. But you will get somewhat of'

[06:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a noticeable jump when you go between the two lenses. Now, if you\'re shooting in 8K, you actually can\'t jump between the lenses once you hit record. So that means if you\'re recording in the 1x lens, you\'ll only be able to go between 1x and 2.9x. And if you\'re shooting on'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the 3x lens, you\'ll actually only be able to go between 3x and 6x. Which does mean you can\'t do 8K and the 12x zoom at the same time, unfortunately. Oh, and if the 1x lens, the 20 mm lens, isn\'t wide'

[06:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enough, Insta360 also has this 15 mm wide-angle lens adapter. So that\'s basically a 0.75x zoom. You can put that on and it\'ll give you a little bit more field [music] of'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'view. Now, let\'s talk about low-light performance. If you\'ve used Insta360 cameras in the past, you\'ll be familiar with the Pure Video mode, a low-light mode that optimizes for shooting in low-light conditions like these that does a fantastic job on increasing the'

[06:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposure in dark scenes so that you can still see details while still managing to keep the digital noise level down. And in scenes where there\'s barely any light, you\'re still able to get an image with enough detail to tell what\'s going on while keeping the footage usable. So'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no matter where you\'re shooting, you won\'t miss [music] an important moment. Something I want to test even further in upcoming videos is going to be just how well the low-light processing holds up because from very brief comparisons, even the 8K I-Log footage, so non-Pure'

[07:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Video footage, looks really good in low-light situations. And yes, as you\'ve seen throughout the video, this camera does have autofocus and there\'s two modes, one continuous where it\'s going to automatically adjust as the subject'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is walking towards or away from the camera, but there\'s also a single shot or single focus mode where you can just tap to focus, let\'s say on the background or on the foreground so that it doesn\'t change as you\'re recording.'

[07:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, let me show you what the bokeh looks like at each of these focal lengths. So, right now I\'m at a composition where my face fills the frame and this is what the bokeh looks like on the 1x zoom. And now this is what the bokeh looks like at the 2x'

[07:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'zoom. And now this is what the bokeh looks like at a 3x zoom. And now this is what the bokeh looks like at a 6x zoom. And I have to drop the resolution down to 4K so I can get to that 12x zoom but this is what the bokeh looks like at'

[08:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that focal length. So, one of my favorite features about these pocket cameras is the fact that they\'re on a gimbal which means they can auto track. And the Luna Ultra has a mode called Deep Track. So, right now'

[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re on the 1x zoom lens so that\'s a 20 mil equivalent and the camera is automatically tracking me as I move around. You can even specify what part of the frame you would like the camera'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to keep you in. And the cool thing about Deep Track is that you can use it in all of the zoom modes. So, we\'re going to go up to 3x, 6x, and 12x. All right, and now we\'re on the 3x zoom, the 60 mil equivalent which is the second lens on'

[08:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the camera. And we\'re going to continue to test and walk around and see how well the camera does tracking me. Now, the cool thing about this feature is that this makes it this camera so useful for'

[08:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'solo content creators. So, imagine if you were a travel creator and you know you\'re traveling by yourself, you don\'t have a camera man. So, that means a lot of your shots are going to end up being static shots if you\'re in the frame. But, with this functionality, now the'

[09:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera can track you and you can add all of that dynamic movement by yourself. All right, so now we\'re on the 6x zoom which is a 120 mm equivalent which is pretty tight. And from the detachable'

[09:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'screen, it looks like it\'s keeping up with me. Now, one thing I do notice is that if you go fast, you\'re definitely going to end up trailing to the edge of the frame as the camera tries to keep up with you and try to predict where you\'re going. So, if you end up moving really'

[09:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fast, there\'s definitely a chance that you lose the tracking. But, if you\'re moving at like a normal speed, the tracking should work just fine. So, now we\'re on the 12x zoom or about a 240 mm equivalent. And I had to drop it down to'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '4K cuz as I said earlier, you can\'t do 12x zoom in the 8K mode, which is totally understandable. And let\'s see how well this tracks me. And as you can see, I\'m definitely trailing towards the'

[09:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edge of the frame. So, it\'ll keep you in frame, but if you\'re moving fast or even at a medium speed, it\'s definitely going to kind of have you lag behind. So, definitely keep that in mind if this is a feature that you\'re really planning on using. I mean, I plan on using it because this makes the shot look so much'

[10:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more dynamic. All right, now we\'re back in 8K. We\'re on the 1x zoom, so the 20 mil lens. I kind of just want to see how far back this will track me. So, I\'m going to go ahead and keep stepping backwards. I\'m about a half court\'s distance away from the camera now. And'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yeah, looks like it\'s still holding on to me. So, I\'m just going to keep going. We\'re going to go like a full court\'s distance away from the camera. By the way, detachable screen, haven\'t lost signal yet. This is a pretty decent distance. All right, so I\'m going to start crossing the court.'

[10:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s see if it keeps up. Yeah, looks like it\'s got me. Okay, I\'m going to go faster now. Woo. Okay. Looks like it didn\'t lose me. That\'s actually really impressive.'

[10:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That\'s awesome. Now, of course, this feature works whether you\'re in front of the camera or behind the camera. And if you\'re behind the camera, that means you can use it to track other subjects, which means you can let the camera and the gimbal do the subject tracking while'

[11:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you focus on things like stability and footwork. Especially useful if you\'re doing something like an orbit shot at 6x zoom, which is really, really difficult to track a subject when you\'re so zoomed in. But, with this feature, makes it a'

[11:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lot easier. So, you can also press the subject track button and then long press the joystick and it will go ahead and select all the subjects in the scene to group track. That way, both of us stay in the scene instead of just tracking a'

[11:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'single person, they can track both of us. Now, let\'s quickly talk about stabilization. All the footage you\'ve seen so far has been a mix of me just walking with the camera just casually and also footage where I\'ve been doing the, you know, what you call the ninja'

[11:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'walk to get more stable footage. But, you can also see just how stable the footage can get with added stabilization in post-production as well. One of the things about stabilization is actually that the lighter the camera gets, the harder it is to get that super steady'

[11:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot because if it\'s so lightweight, it\'s kind of easy to accidentally move it around and end up introducing some of that camera shake. But, what surprised me is that the stabilization performance has been really exceptional. Even zoomed in at 12 times digital zoom, I\'m able to'

[12:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get incredibly smooth tracking shots. All right, let\'s take a look at the design and build quality of the Luna Ultra. First of all, with no accessories attached, the Luna Ultra truly is a very pocketable camera. It\'s compact and it\'s'

[12:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lightweight and it\'s super easy to take with you, whether in a little sling bag or just straight up in your pocket. The top of the camera features the gimbal head with the two camera design that tucks away when powered off. On the back of the Luna Ultra, you\'ll find the'

[12:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'built-in mic with the pre-installed wind guard. On the side of the Luna Ultra, you\'ll find a cover that protects the microSD card slot. And on the back of the Luna Ultra, you\'ll find the control interface featuring the touchscreen, but we\'ll get to that in a moment. Before'

[12:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that though, you\'ll see that the camera has a 5D joystick, which can be used to control things like gimbal movement. And you can click it in once to start and stop subject tracking, twice to recenter the gimbal, and three times to flip the camera around 180°. To the right of'

[12:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that, you\'ll find the zoom rocker which can be held down to zoom in and out gradually or a single push up or down will jump up or down zoom levels from one times to two [music] times to three times to six times to 12 times. On the'

[13:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'touchscreen itself, you\'ll find a really familiar control scheme to other Insta360 products like their Ace Pro 2. A swipe down gives you access to the general camera settings. A swipe right opens your gallery of your photos and videos. A swipe up lets you change the'

[13:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'resolution and frame rate settings. A swipe left opens the camera settings where you can adjust your white balance, exposure, color profiles, sharpness, and change your autofocus modes. You\'ll also notice two buttons on the bottom of the'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'touchscreen. These are custom function buttons. So, you can assign these to a variety of different camera controls, giving you fast access to things like adjusting your exposure or switching between photo and video modes. Now, while the camera uses microSD cards, the'

[13:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Luna Ultra also has 47GB of internal storage, which is great if you forget your card or if you run out of storage while you\'re out shooting. When it comes to battery life, you should be able to get up to 4 hours of recording. And with power delivery fast charging, you can'

[13:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get back to shooting in under half an hour. If that\'s not enough battery for you, then you can also use the battery handle for extra battery life up to 2 and 1/2 hours. And with the battery handle or the grip extender, you\'ll also get a 1/4-20 inch mount on the bottom, so you can mount the Luna Ultra to a'

[14:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tripod or other accessories. And since we\'re talking about accessories, I want to show you guys one of my favorite accessories I\'ve been using on the Luna Ultra, and that\'s going to be this piece uh from Ulanzi. It\'s like a multi-accessory. So, first of all, on the bottom here, you\'ll see that it'

[14:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attaches via a 1/4-20 screw, and it gives you an F38 plate, letting you attach this camera to other Ulanzi accessories like my Falcam Tree Root tripod that I love using. On top of that, on the back of the accessory here,'

[14:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll see that it\'s a magnetic plate, letting you attach this to metal surfaces for easy mounting. And if you flip the bottom out, you\'ll see that there\'s also a little hook, so you can attach it to door frames or to railings. And if you flip this over, you\'ll see'

[14:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you also get a little tripod feet, so that way you can use this as a tabletop stand. And that\'s not all. You can also flip it around and use this as an extended selfie stick. Or even better, you can flip it'

[14:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'around again, and now you have a low-angle briefcase handle to get those low-angle shots and maintain that stability and smoothness. This thing is so cool. If you guys are interested in this, I\'ll have a link to that in the description below as well. Okay, so'

[15:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ve got to talk about one of the most unique features on the Luna Ultra, and that\'s going to be the fact that this screen is detachable, which is something that is I I really haven\'t seen on any other camera,'

[15:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really. And when you detach it, it is not only a wireless remote, letting you control the camera, but it\'s also a wireless monitor, letting you kind of preview what the camera sees even when you\'re not next to the camera, which is'

[15:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'game-changing for a small pocket camera like this. Now, let me walk you through some of the features. Fun fact, this remote is also actually a microphone. So, when you\'re recording from far away, you can actually use this as a wireless'

[15:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mic, and you don\'t even have to own a wireless mic like the mic pros, but we\'ll talk about that in the audio test section. First of all, let\'s talk about what you can control using the detachable screen. So, of course, you have all of your normal functionality,'

[16:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like being able to use the joystick the same way that you\'re able to double tap the center, triple tap to rotate the camera around, being able to single tap to track subjects and untrack subjects, being able to start stop recording,'

[16:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'zoom. And then, on top of that, you still have all of the touchscreen controls. So, now you don\'t even need to use a mobile phone app. You can just use a physical controller, which is so nice. So, let me give you a really good'

[16:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example of why I love this detachable screen. Normally, if you wanted to get a shot and you\'re by yourself and you set up a tripod, you kind of had to pre-frame what you wanted the shot to look like. But now, with a detachable screen wireless monitor situation, I can'

[16:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of get to my spot, figure out, "Okay, that looks good. Let me go ahead and punch in. Let me go ahead and reframe a little bit, so I\'m on like the right third. Okay, that framing looks good. Oh, no, the lighting\'s changing." So, you know, you can change your'

[16:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposure settings, and then you can go ahead and walk out of frame, and then come back in and get your shot super quickly. You don\'t have to run over to the camera to check to make sure'

[17:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything looked good. If you If you wanted to, you could preview the footage right here on the detachable screen, if that\'s the way you wanted to do it. Like, this detachable screen is genuinely game-changing, and I think is what sets it apart from any other camera I\'ve been using recently, cuz this is so'

[17:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'convenient. At first, I really thought that this was like ah this is kind of gimmicky, but it wasn\'t until last week when Annette and I were hanging out with our friends Ryan and Erica at their house and we were playing like on their pool table that I just plopped the Luna Ultra onto the pool table and I just'

[17:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'took off the detachable screen and I started getting a bunch of different angles all without really trying. A few shots where I like punched in to get some cool tight detail shots [music] of the cue ball and then here and there I'

[17:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would go ahead and just track one of us and let the camera [music] do the thing. And I got like a dozen angles from just plopping a camera down on a table. It\'s literally never been easier. Like just now I was recording, I peeked down, I\'m like ah I\'m cutting off my head a little'

[17:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bit so let me just go ahead and pan up just the teeny bit. Boom, there we go, done. So easy. Now, I don\'t know if Insta360 has it listed anywhere on their website for the max transmission distance for the detachable screen. If I'

[18:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'find it, I\'ll put it on screen right now, but I\'ve been able to at least use it for the length of a basketball court which is like 90 something feet or about almost 30 m with [music] zero drop-off issues and it works perfectly. I\'m'

[18:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'obsessed with this thing. Having this detachable screen really changes how you can shoot with the pocket [music] camera like this and there\'s even a really funny example on Insta360\'s website where basically you'

[18:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hand off the camera to somebody else and then you know you\'re the subject but you\'re also taking the the controller to frame yourself up. Basically turning your significant other into a human tripod which of for some people that might be the move. All right, so next'

[18:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s talk about the audio coming out of the Insta360 Luna Ultra. Right now, you\'re listening to the internal microphone that\'s built in to the camera itself with none of the noise reduction or vocal enhancement options turned on and this is what the audio sounds like'

[18:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'coming straight out of the camera. And earlier I was telling you about the fact that this detachable screen has a bunch of different features and one of those things is it has a built-in microphone right there and you can turn that on in the settings and now you\'re listening to'

[19:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the audio that\'s coming from the detachable screen. So, this is super clutch if you don\'t want to bring a wireless mic with you, and you want it audio, and you also want it to be filming away from the camera. This means that you have a wireless mic with you'

[19:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s built into the detachable screen. How cool is that? You can also pair Bluetooth microphones like Insta360\'s own brand new mic pros, and now you can have even better audio quality wirelessly, so you can move around your'

[19:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame away from the camera, closer to the camera, and still get crystal clear audio. This whole ecosystem so far is really well thought out. Now, in case you were wondering about wind noise reduction like I was, first of all, the'

[19:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'camera itself has a pre-installed built-in windscreen that helps cut down on wind noise. And right now, it\'s not the craziest windy environment, but I am riding through on my One Wheel through'

[20:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and generating some wind right now, so there should be a little bit of wind noise. I\'m curious how that\'s going to show up on camera, but there\'s also wind reduction settings built into the camera as well. So, let\'s go ahead and turn'

[20:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'those on. All right, and now we\'ve got the auto wind noise reduction feature turned on, and the wind\'s picking up just a little bit right now, and I\'m curious to hear how that sounds in comparison. And then, there\'s one more mode as well. And now, you\'re listening'

[20:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the voice enhancement feature turned on, which should isolate the voice more. I think of this is kind of like noise reduction that\'s more than just wind noise reduction, right? That\'s it\'s that background noise reduction as well. So,'

[20:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s hear how that sounds. Actually, let me go back to where there was like equipment going on in the background where there was like loud noises, and we\'ll see how this works over there. And now, I\'ve got the voice enhancement mode turned on, which should be a little bit'

